    <section id="whats-causing-it" class="reveal">
      <h2>What's Causing It</h2>

      <p>The most unsettling aspect of chronic inflammation is that its primary causes are features of modern life, not rare exposures or genetic misfortune.</p>

      <h3>Diet</h3>

      <p>Ultra-processed foods — which now account for more than half of the caloric intake in countries like the United States and United Kingdom — are among the most reliably pro-inflammatory inputs a human body can receive. Refined carbohydrates spike blood glucose, triggering inflammatory signaling. Some researchers have hypothesized that high omega-6 intake shifts eicosanoid balance toward inflammation, though large meta-analyses have not consistently found that dietary linoleic acid increases inflammatory markers — making this contested rather than settled. Emulsifiers and artificial additives appear to compromise the gut lining, allowing bacterial components to leak into systemic circulation and trigger immune responses. The Mediterranean diet's association with lower inflammatory markers is, in this light, not a mystery: it is the rough inverse of the above.</p>

      <h3>Sleep Deprivation</h3>

      <p>Even a single night of poor sleep measurably elevates inflammatory markers. Chronic sleep restriction — less than six hours per night, sustained over weeks — produces levels of IL-6 and TNF-&alpha; comparable to low-grade inflammatory disease. The mechanism involves the immune system's circadian regulation: inflammatory processes are normally suppressed during deep sleep as part of the body's repair cycle. Truncate the sleep, truncate the repair.</p>

      <h3>Chronic Stress</h3>

      <p>The stress hormone cortisol is, acutely, anti-inflammatory. The body deploys it to modulate immune responses during threats. But chronic stress desensitizes immune cells to cortisol's signal — a process called glucocorticoid resistance — leaving the inflammatory response without its normal brake. Remarkably, this desensitization can be detected at the cellular level in people reporting high chronic stress, even when their cortisol levels look normal on a blood test.</p>

      <h3>Sedentary Behavior</h3>

      <p>Exercise is one of the most potent anti-inflammatory interventions known. Muscle contractions release a class of signaling proteins called myokines, several of which directly suppress inflammatory cytokines. Skeletal muscle, when regularly used, functions as an endocrine organ that actively regulates systemic inflammation. A body that doesn't move loses that regulation.</p>

      <h3>Environmental Exposures</h3>

      <p>Microplastics, air pollution, and persistent organic pollutants have each been shown to activate inflammatory pathways. PFAS compounds — the so-called forever chemicals found in non-stick cookware, food packaging, and water supplies — trigger immune dysregulation. These aren't theoretical risks; the exposures are near-universal in industrialized populations.</p>
    </section>

