    <section id="the-measurement-problem" class="reveal">
      <h2>The Measurement Problem</h2>

      <p>One reason chronic inflammation has taken so long to be taken seriously as a clinical priority is that it's genuinely difficult to measure in ways that translate to practice.</p>

      <p>The most widely used marker is high-sensitivity C-reactive protein (hs-CRP), a protein produced by the liver in response to inflammatory cytokines. It's inexpensive, widely available, and has strong predictive value for cardiovascular events and all-cause mortality. A level below 1 mg/L is generally considered low risk; 1–3 mg/L is moderate; above 3 mg/L is high. Most standard physicals don't include it.</p>

      <p>Other markers with emerging evidence include:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>IL-6</strong> — one of the primary upstream cytokines, more sensitive than CRP but less standardized</li>
        <li><strong>Fibrinogen</strong> — a clotting protein that rises with inflammation and predicts cardiovascular risk</li>
        <li><strong>White blood cell count</strong> — crude but informative; chronically elevated counts in the normal range correlate with worse outcomes</li>
        <li><strong>Insulin resistance markers (HOMA-IR)</strong> — metabolic inflammation driver increasingly recognized as more predictive than lipid ratios</li>
      </ul>

      <p>The honest caveat is that no single marker fully captures the complexity of systemic inflammatory status. A panel approach is more informative than any individual test, and interpretation requires clinical context. But some measurement is substantially better than none, and the current clinical default — measuring nothing unless something has already gone wrong — is increasingly difficult to justify.</p>
    </section>

