    <section id="what-actually-works" class="reveal">
      <h2>What Actually Works</h2>

      <p>The research on anti-inflammatory interventions has both genuine good news and a lot of noise to cut through.</p>

      <h3>What the Evidence Supports</h3>

      <p><strong>Omega-3 fatty acids.</strong> The most consistent supplementation evidence in this space. Marine-sourced EPA and DHA measurably shift the lipid balance toward anti-inflammatory pathways. Effect sizes are modest at lower doses; studies using 2–4g daily of combined EPA/DHA show more robust effects on IL-6 and TNF-&alpha;.</p>

      <p><strong>Exercise.</strong> Non-negotiable, and there's no supplement substitute. Both aerobic exercise and resistance training reduce inflammatory markers, with Zone 2 aerobic work (sustained moderate intensity) showing particularly strong effects on systemic inflammation over time. The dose-response relationship appears to be real: more is better, up to a point that most people will never reach.</p>

      <p><strong>Sleep.</strong> Treating sleep as a recoverable luxury is exactly wrong. Seven to nine hours per night for most adults isn't a lifestyle preference; it's a biological requirement for inflammatory homeostasis. The research on sleep extension — deliberately adding sleep time — shows measurable reductions in inflammatory markers within weeks.</p>

      <p><strong>Dietary pattern.</strong> The evidence for specific anti-inflammatory foods is messier than it's often presented. But the evidence for overall dietary pattern is robust. Less ultra-processed food, more vegetables, legumes, fish, and olive oil, fewer refined carbohydrates and industrial seed oils — the Mediterranean pattern, broadly interpreted — consistently associates with lower inflammatory markers and better health outcomes.</p>

      <p><strong>Stress regulation.</strong> The mechanism is real; the interventions are less standardized. Mindfulness-based stress reduction has the strongest evidence base among behavioral interventions for reducing inflammatory markers. The effect sizes are not large, but they are replicable.</p>

      <h3>What's Not Well-Established</h3>

      <p>Most individual supplements marketed as "anti-inflammatory" — curcumin, quercetin, resveratrol — have impressive results in cell culture and disappointing results in humans. Bioavailability is typically the problem: these compounds don't survive the digestive process in forms that produce systemic effects at realistic doses. Some formulations have improved this picture, but the evidence remains thin relative to the marketing.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="why-this-matters" class="reveal">
      <h2>Why This Matters More Than Most Health Topics</h2>

      <p>There is something philosophically uncomfortable about chronic inflammation as a concept. It doesn't have a clean story arc — no infection to fight, no obvious enemy, no single drug to take. It's the product of how we eat, move, sleep, and exist in a polluted, stressed, sedentary world. The interventions aren't dramatic.</p>

      <p>But that's also what makes it unusual among health topics: the evidence for prevention is actually quite strong. The mechanisms are known. The behavioral modifications are not exotic. For most people, the inflammatory trajectory is not fixed.</p>

      <p>The fire can be banked, if not extinguished. That's a more actionable message than most medicine offers.</p>
    </section>

